Brexit market sell-off in charts

2016-06-24

Britain’s vote to leave the EU has shocked markets that had become increasingly confident the UK would remain.

The pound tumbled to a 30-year low of $1.3224, breaking the $1.40 level that has been the floor for the currency since the mid-1980s. Sterling also racked up significant declines against the euro and the yen.

UK gilts surged with, the benchmark 10-year bond yield falling 35 basis points to a record low of 1.02 per cent.

UK stock markets plunged at the open, with the FTSE 100 falling 8.7 percent before recovering to trade down 4.4 per cent by noon. 

.

The mid-cap FTSE 250 index, whose member companies earn about 70 per cent of their revenues in the UK, fell 12 per cent at the open.

Persimmon, the UK’s biggest housebuilder, made the biggest single loss on the FTSE 100 in early trading while Royal Bank of Scotland led the financial sector lower.

